column15: People don't understand how important it is to remain gluten-free, especially when dealing with Celiac's disease. Any trace of gluten products will make me sick for the rest of the day (sometimes longer), and not only are people insensitive to the topic, but they generally do not have any comprehension on how serious it can be.
column24: Diagnosed with Celiac's disease one year ago.

column7: Shelf life
column15: Manager and kitchen staff's knowledge. Proving they know how careful they need to be means a lot. I once traveled to Philly and saw a restaurant that said they had gluten free bread for philly cheese steaks. When I got there I saw they were cutting the bread on the same board with the same knife. Some places will take the croutons off the salad and serve the salad back. A lot of people don't know how careful they need to be so reviews are very important when I decide in particular about how careful the staff is.

column15: If they will accommodate me and my gf requests.  Sometimes I bring my own bun and want them to heat it up safely.  If they can do that, it goes a long way in my enjoyment of the experience.  Also, the servers need to know what is in everything and how things are prepared.  I need to know if the french fries are actually hand cut at the restaurant or if they are frozen.  It makes me really angry when they don't know or if they lie.

column15: I just won't chance a place that doesn't seem to give a crap about special diets. It's a crap shoot. Honestly, I end up cooking because the chains (except Chipotle) that support GF are far away and the local places that I REALLY want to support charge so much extra that we have to budget to go out to eat. That's not a bad thing, mind. It's like how my family did growing up. Going out becomes a treat.
